    "short_title": "How Spaceflight Alters Fruit Fly Gene Expression",
    "study_publication_title": "Innate Immune Responses of Drosophila melanogaster Are Altered by Spaceflight",
    "short_description": "This NASA study explored how spaceflight changes gene activity in fruit flies, revealing how microgravity and radiation affect immunity and development during flight aboard the Space Shuttle Discovery (STS-121).",
    "summary": "This experiment examined how living in space changes the way genes are expressed in fruit flies, an important model organism for human biology. Researchers sent flies aboard the Space Shuttle Discovery (STS-121) for nearly 13 days, allowing them to breed and develop in microgravity. Using whole-body gene analysis, the team compared space-grown larvae and adults with Earth-raised controls. The results showed that spaceflight altered genes tied to immune defense, stress, and cellular metabolism. Flies raised in space had weakened innate immune signaling and disrupted macrophage-like cell development, echoing concerns about immune suppression in astronauts. This work deepens NASA’s understanding of biological adaptation to microgravity, guiding strategies to safeguard astronaut health on long-duration missions.",
    "description": "NASA scientists used fruit flies (Drosophila melanogaster) to study how spaceflight alters gene activity and immune system function. Flies were raised aboard the Space Shuttle Discovery during mission STS-121 (July 4–17, 2006), at an orbital altitude of about 330 km. The flies developed entirely in microgravity, producing a new generation in space. On landing, researchers collected larvae and adults, extracted RNA, and performed genome-wide expression profiling using Affymetrix microarrays. They found significant shifts in genes controlling innate immunity, including those regulating macrophage development, pathogen recognition, and antimicrobial peptide production. Some stress and repair genes were also more active, suggesting that space conditions trigger physiological strain. These findings demonstrate that even short-term exposure to spaceflight can reprogram immune gene networks, providing crucial insight for understanding health risks during extended human missions beyond Earth orbit.",
