    "summary": "NASA researchers examined how the thymus, a key immune organ, responds to spaceflight. Young adult mice (C57BL/6NTac) were flown aboard the Space Shuttle Endeavour (STS-118) for 13 days. Thymus tissue from space-flown mice was compared to ground-based controls using microarrays to analyze gene expression. The study found significant changes in genes regulating stress, glucocorticoid receptors, and T cell activity, helping explain immune system challenges observed during space missions.",
    "description": "Understanding how spaceflight impacts immune organs is vital for astronaut health. In this experiment, young adult mice were housed in Animal Enclosure Modules (AEMs) both on Earth and aboard the Space Shuttle Endeavour for nearly two weeks. Researchers harvested thymus tissue shortly after landing and used microarrays to profile gene expression. The analysis revealed that spaceflight induced notable changes in genes controlling stress responses, glucocorticoid receptor pathways, and T cell signaling. About 970 gene probes showed significant changes, with 12 genes exhibiting strong up- or down-regulation (≥1.5-fold change). These results demonstrate that microgravity and spaceflight-associated stressors can modify thymus function at the molecular level, contributing to immune system alterations observed in astronauts.",
